          "Process Mining",
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "203 Non-Native English Students",
          "1 Academic English Writing Course",
          "Pre-test Scores, LMS logs",
          "Winne and Hadwin’s SRL model",
          "[Monitoring Orientation, Elaboration, Planning, First re-reading, Re-reading, Evaluation]",
          "Authors take interactions of users with LMS to make a taxonomy of actions that, together can be subsequently divided in SRL processes.  \n\nAuthors find 3 typical sequences of behavior that lead and translate to 3 patterns of learning behavior. These were compared using the McNemar-Bowker test, with Bonferroni correction being applied to control for family-wise error rate. ",
          "FOMM",
          "-",
          "3",
          "Group 1: Read and write simultaneously - students who tented to exhibit the highest rates of re-readiing while continuoulsy re-directing their writing to meet the specifications. \n\nGroup 2: Write Intensively, Read Selectively - They start to write early and dedicate substancially more time to writing than their peers. \n\nGroup 3: Read-first, then write -",
          "SRL is more dynamic than initially expected. One of the reasons for this sort of behavior relates with the fact that learners often fail to fulfill on their own promises and expectations. \n\nThis may stem from the fact that learning conditions change and from it learners my update their behavior.",
          "Authors use FOMM to create 3 clusters of behavior when it comes to planning and execution of a writing task. ",
          "Task was time-limited.\n\nSmall number of submissions of changed plans."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 9
    }
